# Steps to reproduce the problem
1. Setup a generic message sender function with a Promise.race that will reject after a timeout.

return Promise.race<T>([
            new Promise<T>((resolve, reject) => {
                chrome.runtime.sendMessage(this.id, message, (data: T) => {
                    if (chrome.runtime.lastError) {
                        reject(chrome.runtime.lastError.message);
                        return;
                    }

                    resolve(data);
                });
            }),
            new Promise<T>((_resolve, reject) => {
                setTimeout(reject, 2000);
            }),
        ]);

2. Use above to create a custom message to send

send({ type: "some-type" })

3. Setup a message processor (in a chrome plugin - with manifest 3)

chrome.runtime.onMessageExternal.addListener(
            async (request, _, sendResponse) => {
                if (request.type === "some-type") {
                    const result = await doSomethingAsync();
                    sendResponse(result);
                }
            },
        );

4. Test the send-response. Message will successfully send, but the Promise.race will hit the timeout and thus trigger a failure.

# Problem Description
I have a communication flow setup between my web app and my chrome plugin. The plugin usually communicates an answer back with sendResponse, so that I can process any result in the web app.
I've noticed that the latest Canary build has broken something in this flow. Not sure when it started, but it did work before.
Beta still works as expected.

# Summary
chrome.runtime.sendMessage does not trigger the responseCallback

# Custom Questions
#### Which component does this fall under?
Not sure - I don't know

#### Does this work in other browsers? 
Yes - This is just a Chrome problem

# Additional Data
Category: API \
