Regression: Yes

# Steps to reproduce the problem
1. Take the existing sidepanel.open sample here: https://github.com/GoogleChrome/chrome-extensions-samples/tree/main/functional-samples/cookbook.sidepanel-open
2. Add to manifest.json: "omnibox": { "keyword" : "test" }
3. Add to service-worker.js the following: 
chrome.omnibox.onInputEntered.addListener(function (text, disposition) {
  console.log('inputEntered: ' + text);
  chrome.tabs.query({ active: true, currentWindow: true }, (tabs) => {
      if (tabs.length > 0) {
          const tab = tabs[0];
          chrome.sidePanel.open({ windowId: tab.windowId });
      }
  });  
});
4. Load extension. Go into omnibox and type "test something" and [ENTER]

5. Note: pre-initializing the windowId variable so all that's in the listener is the chrome.sidePanel.open call doesn't help. 

# Problem Description
When you try to call sidePanel.open from the chrome.omnibox.onInputEntered event listener in a Chrome Extension, you get the following error:

`sidePanel.open()` may only be called in response to a user gesture error. 

It seems like the user entering something in the omnibox should qualify as a user gesture. 

# Summary
Cannot call sidepanel.open from chrome.omnibox.onInputEntered event listener in Chrome Extension.

# Custom Questions
